wKuHaN0K_mMfPxRvIP0EEXKl63uLlR1jXHRUqTfA227lI5jST0UZqco-1av4L_oH9EiKUw]. Re=
ad the descriptions of the artists and their work at the top of each page, =
and then compare paintings by Returns or Sale Price to start to understand =
which pieces collectors value most.
You=E2=80=99ll notice, though, while you=E2=80=99re exploring, that not eve=
ry artist or work is in the database. To ensure accuracy and consistency, a=
nd to generate a return metric, Masterworks doesn=E2=80=99t include paintin=
gs that haven=E2=80=99t been sold at auction at least twice.=C2=A0
For example, when I read about Salvator Mundi, I obviously searched Leonard=
o da Vinci, but came up empty-handed. I thought there was an error, so I re=
ached out to Jason Papodopoulos, who runs data science at Masterworks to as=
k about the omission. His answer was more fascinating than I could have hop=
ed for, and I=E2=80=99ll repost it here in full:=C2=A0
Regarding da Vinci, we have not identified any da Vinci auction results exc=
ept Salvator Mundi, meaning not even works that have been sold once. We hav=
e, however, identified multiple works by followers or artists of his circle=
=2E His works never come at auction, and when they do, you see what happens.
In the case of Salvator Mundi (see: Christie=E2=80=99s [https://email.mg2.s=
ubstack.com/c/eJxFkMGOhCAMhp9muGkoKqMHDnvZ1zAIdYYMggtV17dfxjls0rRJmz9f-hlN-=
IjpVGvMxN5tpHNFFfDIHokwsS1jGp1VIEXfdO3ArGot9F3PXB7nhLho5xWlDdm6Td4ZTS6GK8G5=
6NhTcaFNK9pJDOZuhrkdeINz3_ec39upl_OHqzfrMBhUuGM6Y0Dm1ZNozbfm6ya-Sx3HUZtncpk=
c5trEpex8pE-vPMagk42V1dXugnEVtJ2ooIOhytrvmmKqli1YV0kA3smmBJlTggvgIACaDrisoe=
a_P_srHI1bYL61fHmIOm9TJm1ebyhLKkSaYnLhUc6vp17QX4fy_lhmYTg6Rwx68mg_Zugj-HI1P=
jBgKuLtqKloBRDNnUv5dnuZKOoakP0gObBCtrGkwj_0D0Nhkms] ), its Provenance (list=
 of prior ownership) does mention 2 public sales. One may think that this m=
akes the work a repeat-sale pair. However, a major factor in the Old Master=
s market is attribution and authentication. In the past, the work was attri=
buted to Giovanni Antonio Boltraffio, and was sold for =C2=A345. After rese=
arch, specialists concluded [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE2OgzAMh=
U_T7Iri_FC6yGI2cw0UEheiQsIkpgy3n5QuRrJsyU_20_ucJRxTPsyaCrF36-lY0UTcy4xEmNlW=
MPfBG2hFJ7W6M2-Uh053LJT-kREXG2ZDeUO2bsMcnKWQ4nnBudBsMlarm3ZOoPRCDNY9VKfghl5=
aZUE7__G1mw8YHRp8YT5SRDabiWgtF_l1Ed-19n1vaErbOJFLjUtL3RU7vyylfF226MMVOik6YM=
EILoCDAJAaeNtAw39_Xs-4y7DA46L4MoqmbEMh657vVyybmGhIOcSxys_JLjifQg3V11n_Bzp6j=
HaY0X_y0gfbSaAfMWKuOH1vqcICEPLG2_ZN7MxXgUhou3vLgVVnn-pV_Df9AwpOhmM] that it=
 was actually a da Vinci. Hence, the assumption that you can calculate the =
return of a work because an artwork doesn't change is challenged in such ca=
ses.=C2=A0
Under our research framework, we do not include works that faced issues wit=
h attribution and/or authentication. This is one of the reasons why we are =
also not involved in the Old Masters market.
There=E2=80=99s so much in that answer. No da Vinci painting has ever chang=
ed hands twice in a public auction, and Salvator Mundi is the only known da=
 Vinci to sell at auction. That explains why it was the most expensive sale=
 of all-time. The only other time the work went up for sale at auction, it =
was actually under another artist=E2=80=99s name, which allowed it to slip =
under the radar and sell for =C2=A345. Once da Vinci was confirmed as the a=
rtist, the price shot up over 7 million times!
The answer also shows the rigorous approach Masterworks takes to its price =
database. It=E2=80=99s more than just a fun and educational tool for explor=
ation; that=E2=80=99s a byproduct. More importantly, it underpins the trans=
formation of the art market from a wealthy collectors=E2=80=99 playground t=
o an investable asset class.=C2=A0
Art as an Asset Class
Art is a $1.7 trillion asset class that most of us don=E2=80=99t think of a=
s an asset class.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s also one of the oldest. Before Patrick Drahi (a billionaire ar=
t collector, of course) took it private [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/e=
JxFkE2OhCAQhU_T7Nrwo2gvWMxmrmEQSiWt4EDZjrefansxCSlIvVQ93ucswpTyabZUkL1Lj-cG=
JsJRFkCEzPYCuQ_eCC071dQP5k3tRdd0LJR-zACrDYvBvAPb9mEJzmJI8ZrgXDZsNmPdNq17aDt=
q1w0eamk1V6puHYzCa_7xtbsPEB0YeEE-UwS2mBlxKzf1dZPfdJ4xHQv4CapjthlTrPYNYqzA76=
RSJ7gF6FUSzjCc5T6lEKf7lsOLYpLAgpFcCi6kEKoRXFei4r8_r2c8VFjFeKv5Osmq7ENB656VS=
yvLJiYcUqZNJD9nu8JyCRS2p3vdY8Czh2gH-tuHA35wXmT6CSJk8ve9RYIohFQt1_pN8spNoJTQ=
3UNzwcjZJ5qK_6Z_AoiP1Q] last year for $3.7 billion, auction house Sotheby=
=E2=80=99s was the oldest company on the NYSE.
$68 billion worth of art changed hands in 2019, but unless your friends are=
 particularly artsy or particularly wealthy, you probably don=E2=80=99t kno=
w the people attached to many of those hands. I polled my Twitter followers=
 this week, and only 13% allocate to art.=C2=A0
I asked those who do own art to reply with the percentage of their portfoli=
o they allocate to it, and very few replied=E2=80=A6 because investing in a=
rt is synonymous with being really rich, and no one wants to come out and s=
ay, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m really rich.=E2=80=9D In fact, the first reply to =
the tweet was, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m not rich. [https://email.mg2.substack.c=
om/c/eJxFkM9ugzAMxp-GHKv8AQKHHCZNfYGddkKBuDQqJCxx2vH2M_QwKXJsJZ8_-zdZhDmm3W=
wxIzvCgPsGJsArL4AIiZUMafDOiFZ2qql75kztRNd0zOfhlgBW6xeDqQDbyrj4yaKP4VRwLht2N=
w5cz6EhCQeo1U3XfTdOWgotnG6sffva4jyECQw8Ie0xAFvMHXHLlfqo5JUOvvwx0WWKK1VfmCyW=
_B1LmKnMeFSUCNUIJVXHteop73qtK3WlLp-SM28kl4ILKY5vvL2IC__9eT7CS_lV3Kqar7O85DJ=
Su-lxOLFkQsQxJk82NX_c7QrL-UDbDnSvJXjcBwh2XMC9QeCb54lmmCEAjQpusEgUhZBK87Y9UJ=
6LEykl2q5vuWDk7CKpwr_pH8qIi14]=E2=80=9D
It=E2=80=99s a shame that art, like many of the best performing asset class=
es, has been unattainable to all but the wealthiest of the wealthy. Particu=
larly at a time when people are piling into Bitcoin and gold to hedge again=
st inflation with rates at all-time lows, blue-chip art is a smart piece of=
 a diversified portfolio.=C2=A0
According to Citi [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkUtv4yAUhX9NWFo8DHY=
WLKo-1C6qqp3NzAphuE6QbXDhOk3-_ZBkpJEQcDn36ojvOItwSPmi11SQXDeDlxV0hJ8yAyJksh=
XIJnjNFO-FbPfE69azXvYkFDNmgMWGWWPegKzbMAdnMaR4m6CUS3LUo1UtZwMFOgouGbNgHe-4B=
-okV9zdfe3mA0QHGk6QLykCmfURcS078bDjL3XZUgBL43D8d4uA9Xnrxs2uMnyX07mW4uN1j797=
mD_Xlz_P4vPp_Pz2a7oKvfSOCdvvlXOtFZ5D13feqW6kVFJZWx4DBvOQ0bzbPAGaL1hTrThl-2b=
1IwmaU84o44wJyahqWEPP36cp_oiwsHHX0uXAm7INBa2bGpcWknVMOKQc4qHK09EuMN-ECsvUc9=
liwIuBaIcZ_J0j3uO4kTUHiJBrTN5YrCEwxkVHlbomceNWQQum6qcoI9XZpzoV_5v-BcqaoYc],=
 =E2=80=9CArt could gain increasing recognition as an investment asset clas=
s over time given its rate of return and lack of correlation with major ass=
et classes.=E2=80=9D
On Panic With Friends [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE9vwjAMxT9Nc6z=
ipH_gkAMCsRub2DS2U5W2boloky5xYf32C3CYZNmWn56e_Gs0Ye_8oiYXiN1bRcuEyuItDEiEns=
0BfWVaBYVYyTxbs1ZlLazyFTOh6jziqM2gyM_IprkeTKPJOPtwcC5ydlZS4LouRSZ4U2ImoCzWe=
